post_text: On August 24th the Medway School Board met to address the recent local outbreak of COVID-19. At this meeting it was determined that students will not begin the 2020-2021 school year until September 14th. At that time students will begin in a fully remote mode. The local outbreak is being monitored closely and we will reassess every two weeks. When it is deemed safe, we will return to classrooms in our Hybrid Learning Model that was adopted by the board early in August. You can read the details of each plan on our website. Please email Mrs. Dickinson with questions or concerns.

post_text: Good Morning. Below you will find a letter with updates for the remainder of the school year. I hope you all have taken time to enjoy the vacation week.
text: Good Morning. Below you will find a letter with updates for the remainder of the school year. I hope you all have taken time to enjoy the vacation week.

post_text:
Dear Students and Families,

April vacation is officially upon us. I wish you a restful and healthy week. I’m very proud of the students and families who have taken this incredible challenge placed on us all in stride. I would also like to take this opportunity to thank the teachers who continue to work tirelessly to make the best of what is a terrible situation, the ed techs who work daily to provide additional support to students, the kitchen staff who are continuing to provide food and stability to our students, the bus drivers and ed techs for making those meal deliveries, and the custodians and office staff who are keeping the building going.

The coming weeks will continue to be difficult, but if we continue to support one another we will undoubtedly be successful! I will provide an update for our remote learning plan for the remainder of the year toward the end of the week.

Hoping your week is full of good health, sunshine, and fun!

❤️Mrs. D

post_text: Below you will find an update on the current school closure. Please know that the staff and faculty remain devoted to the well-being and education of our community's students. We are all heartbroken at the course this year has taken. Together the staff is working to ensure that a plan for the remainder of the year is realistic, achievable, and sustainable. We have heard the concerns of our families and students and are working diligently to make this time as positive as possible for all involved. We greatly appreciate the support of our families and community. Please stay safe and take care. ❤️-Mrs. D

post_text:
Dear Families,

We ask that you carry out the following procedure for collecting student work and belongings tomorrow:

-Pull up in front of the main doors
-One person enter the first set of doors and ring the bell
-Give us the name(s) you are picking up for
-We will pass all items out through the window
-If there is a car already at the front, please remain in your vehicle until they have left and then pull up - we will limit to one person in the building at a time
-If you are feeling at all under the weather, have a cough or a fever, do not pick up materials - call us to make other arrangements

We very much appreciate your cooperation as we are taking extra precautions to keep everyone safe!

Katahdin Learning Project is with Beth Whitehouse and 2 others at Katahdin Woods and Waters National Monument.
March 11 at 6:41 PM · Millinocket, ME ·

The eighth grade group from Medway Middle School joined the Katahdin Learning Project today in Katahdin Woods and Waters. One group went snowshoeing with our VIPs (Volunteers in Parks) while another enjoyed the ski loop. It certainly felt like spring as we talked about the many animals homes we passed. We were lucky to have another great group of students and teachers on another beautiful day!

post_text: Thanks to the KLP for a great day in the woods for our 5th graders!
shared_text:
Katahdin Learning Project is in Katahdin Woods and Waters National Monument.
March 3 at 11:13 PM ·

Fifth graders from Medway Middle School came to Katahdin Woods and Waters National Monument to enjoy the cross country ski trails and learn more about animal habitats in the winter. Our VIPs (Volunteers in Parks) Kathy Case, Lou Ellis, and Vicki Richardson helped make this a wonderful day of learning. The 45 degree weather was enjoyed by all as we gained special, sunny views of the East Branch of the Penobscot River and surrounding mountains.

post_text: The student vs. teacher/parent basketball games were a fantastic success (maybe not so much for the students 😉)! We hope everyone has fully recovered! Thank you to everyone who made the night a success, especially Mrs. Whitehouse and Mrs. Thompson for putting it all together, Mrs. Page and Mrs. Gagnon for coaching the student teams, Mr. Page and Mr. Perreault for reffing, Mr. Bouchard and Kaylee for running the clock, Mr. Whitehouse, Mrs. Browne, and Olivia for helping with concessions, and anyone else we might have missed!

post_text: We had a wonderful visit from Greg Johnson, executive director of The Summit Project, who is currently on day 9 of his 150 mile trek from the summit of Cadillac Mountain to the summit of Mt. Katahdin! We are so glad Mr. Johnson could join us and spread the amazing work his organization does to honor our fallen heroes and Gold Star families!
shared_text:
Greg Johnson
October 10, 2019 at 2:57 PM ·

Medway Middle School, thank you for your support and for inviting me to speak to all these wonderful young minds about service, support, and community this morning! You all were AMAZING!!! So grateful for this opportunity!

Maine Heroes are NOT Forgotten!!!
#MHANF

post_text:
WE ARE LOOKING FOR YOUR INPUT!😀

At MMS we are continuously working to make this school the best it can be for all of our students. One way we want to do this is to create a vision shared by the students, staff, and community. This vision will drive all the decisions that affect the education of our students. By answering the following questions, your input will be added to work of creating this important statement about our educational beliefs.

This survey will be open until Monday, October 7th.

post_text: In late August MMS invited any EMPD officer on duty to come in for lunch with the students anytime they had a free moment. Officer Davis was the first person to take us up on our offer today, and the 7th grade even convinced him to join their gym class after! Thanks for visiting, Officer Davis! We look forward to your next visit and visits from your fellow officers!

post_text: Wondering what teachers do on their summer vacation? Today Mrs. Robichaud and her wonderful husband, Mrs. Whitehouse, Mrs. Thompson, and Mrs. Green, along with Mrs. Hale (and her daughter) from the office volunteered their time to paint the school lobby and several classrooms before the new school year begins! That is dedication!!
